    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1843_03_23_page01.jpg"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trim_IE"/>Trim
                        <date when="1843-03-23">March 23 <hi rend="superscript">d</hi> - 43</date>
                        <note place="top">Put a way
                        carefully</note>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    Try if you can<lb/>
                    call to mind having<lb/>
                    published in 1832 <add>with illustrations</add> two<lb/>
                    tiny stories of mine in<lb/>
                    one little vol called<lb/>
                    <title ref="./Workography.xml#Garry1">"Garry Owen" &amp; "Poor Bob the Chimney<lb/>
                    sweeper"</title> I forget everything<lb/>
                    about their coming or going<lb/>
                    into your hands and<lb/>
                    all I want to know about<lb/>
                    The matter is whether I am<lb/>
                    at liberty for any thing you<lb/>
                    care or have a right to care<lb/>
                    to let <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChamR1">Chambers</persName> of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edinburgh_STK"><choice><orig>Edinburg</orig><reg>Edinburgh</reg></choice></placeName><lb/>
                    republish them as he wishes<lb/>
                    to do in his <title ref="./Workography.xml#Chamb2">journal</title> - as I<lb/>
                    should be very glad to let him<lb/>
                    if he like it and if there is<lb/>
                    no reason to the contrary<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">in no ways notwithstanding"</hi><lb/>
                    as the lawyers say -<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    When you answer this, as<lb/>
                    notwithstanding your aversion to<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1843_03_23_page02.jpg"/>
                    answering letters, I take it<lb/>
                    for granted that you or<lb/>
                    your son (my friend or my<lb/>
                    brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1">Francis's</persName> friend &amp; <choice><orig>school-<lb/>
                    fellow</orig><reg>schoolfellow</reg></choice>) certainly will, I beg<lb/>
                    that you will tell me if you<lb/>
                    know, who was the author<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Memoi13">Memoirs of a Peeress<lb/>
                    or<lb/>
                    The days of Charles Fox<lb/>
                    Edited by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BuryC1">Lady Charlotte Bury</persName></title><lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ColbH1">colburn</persName> - 1837<lb/>
                    <note>Though <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Edgeworth</persName> does not know it here, the author of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Memoi13">Memoirs of a Peeress; Or the Days of Fox</title> was novelist and playwright<persName ref="./Personography.xml#GoreC1">Catherine Gore.</persName></note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    In convalescence from a severe<lb/>
                    illness. I have indulged <choice><orig>my,<lb/>
                    self</orig><reg>myself</reg></choice> in reading all the <choice><orig>entertain<lb/>
                    ing</orig><reg>entertaining</reg></choice> &amp; interesting fictions &amp;<lb/>
                    true histories that came within<lb/>
                    my reach.<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    And <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StanP1">Lord Mahons</persName> most<lb/>
                    entertaining and interesting<lb/>
                    <title ref="./Workography.xml#LifeL1">Life of the Grand Condé</title> and this<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">novel</hi>, I do not blush to name<lb/>
                    the <unclear>books</unclear> in the same breath<lb/>
                    have been those which have<lb/>
                    last and most recreated<lb/>
                    me -<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Edited by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BuryC1">Lady <choice><orig>Char</orig><reg>Charlotte</reg></choice></persName><lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1843_03_23_page03.jpg"/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BuryC1"><choice><orig>lotte</orig><reg>Charlotte</reg></choice> Bury</persName> these <title ref="./Workography.xml#Memoi13">memoirs</title> might<lb/>
                    be but written by her I am sure<lb/>
                    they could not be any more than<lb/>
                    by myself - no womans pen<lb/>
                    - a master pen in a master<lb/>
                    hand wrote the view of Paris<lb/>
                    in 1803 &amp; <title ref="./Workography.xml#Memoi13">the death of Fox</title><lb/>
                    and are the specimens or<lb/>
                    imitations of his conversation<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    You must tell me who the<lb/>
                    author was is or is reported<lb/>
                    to be - 
                </p>
                <closer>
                    and I shall be<lb/>
                    Your truly obliged<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
                </closer>
            </div>
